aiobungie.crates

aiobungie crates are a collections of dataclasses which represents a fetched result from the API, specifically using aiobungie.Client.

This client uses the standard aiobungie.Framework entity framework which deserializes raw JSON payloads into a crate, aka a dataclass respectively.

452    )

454        id,
455        aiobungie.MembershipType.STEAM,
456        components,
457        # Assuming the component requires an auth token
458        auth="ACCESS_TOKEN"
459    )
460    print(profile.profiles, profile.characters, profile.profile_inventories)

Concrete implementation of all Bungie components.

Components that requires auth will return None unless an access_token was passed to the request parameters.

Example
import aiobungie

# The components to get and return.
components = (
    aiobungie.ComponentType.PROFILE,
    aiobungie.ComponentType.CHARACTERS,
    aiobungie.ComponentType.PROFILE_INVENTORIES,
)
profile = await client.fetch_profile(
    id,
    aiobungie.MembershipType.STEAM,
    components,
    # Assuming the component requires an auth token
    auth="ACCESS_TOKEN"
)
print(profile.profiles, profile.characters, profile.profile_inventories)

class Unique(abc.ABC): 
 55class Unique(abc.ABC):
 56    """An interface for common fields that Destiny2/Bungie membership/user objects has.
 57
 58    You can use this interface as a type hint for objects that contains minimal information.
 59
 60    Example
 61    -------
 62    ```py
 63    def print_options(user: crates.Unique) -> None:
 64        print(
 65        "Welcome", user.unique_name,
 66        "You membership type is", user.type,
 67        "You profile link is", user.link
 68    )
 69
 70    my_user = await client.fetch_bungie_user(00000)
 71    print_options(my_user) # accepts a bungie user.
 72
 73    my_friends = await client.fetch_friends('token')
 74    for friend in my_friends:
 75        print_options(friend) # Friend is also unique
 76    ```
 77    """
 78
 79    __slots__ = ()
 80
 81    @property
 82    @abc.abstractmethod
 83    def id(self) -> int:
 84        """The user's id."""
 85

 89        """The user's name."""

 94        """The membership type of this user."""

 96    @property

 99        """The user like's unique display name code.
100
101        This can be `None` if the user hasn't logged in after season of the lost update.
102        """
103

106        """The user like's display name. This includes the full name with the user name code."""
107        return f"{self.name}#{self.code}"

The result of a partial BungieUser information. also known as battle-net membership.

The difference between the two is that some memberships return information about their Bungie user, but is incomplete, so this get used instead.

This is what's used for objects that contain .bungie_user field, for an example ClanMember.bungie_user

You can fetch the actual bungie user of this partial user by using PartialBungieUser.fetch_self() method.
